The Khephari are massive scarab-beetle folk with bronze chitinous shells.
They stand a full head above most humans and carry considerable weight.
Their theology centers on the cycle: decay and renewal are the same process at different moments.
Every Khephari undergoes a molting transformation understood as true death and rebirth. Rare elders survive a second molting.
They possess vibration-sensing organs in their feet that read earth-speech: tremors, settling bedrock, buried chambers.
They built the enduring roads to and from the Great Pyramid. Khephari roads do not crack or shift.
They filed seismic warnings about the Cinderteeth eruption with Keeper survey offices. The warnings were ignored.
They are patient beyond human measure and do not require acknowledgment for their work.
They are valued as engineers, surveyors, and builders across the known world.
Their relationship with human institutions is one of weary experience: they contribute, credit goes elsewhere.
They share with the Ashborn a pattern of essential labor without institutional recognition.
